===2000=== {| class="wikitable" width="100%" ! width="125" | Date !Event |- | 1 November | [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1326]] accepts the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia membership into the United Nations. Yugoslavia rejoined the [[United Nations General Assembly]] as a new member. |}
===2001=== {| class="wikitable" width="100%" ! width="125" | Date !Event |- | June 2001 | The five successor states drafted and signed an Agreement on Succession Issues.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.dipublico.com.ar/english/yugoslav-agreement-on-succession-issues-2001/ | title = Yugoslav Agreement on Succession Issues (2001) | accessdate = 2012-06-14 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|jstor=20694208|title=AGREEMENT ON SUCCESSION ISSUES BETWEEN THE FIVE SUCCESSOR STATES OF THE FORMER STATE OF YUGOSLAVIA|date=1 January 2002|journal=International Legal Materials|volume=41|issue=1|pages=3–36|via=|doi=10.2307/20694208|doi-broken-date=2018-09-21}}</ref> |}
===2006=== {| class="wikitable" width="100%" ! width="125" | Date !Event |- | 21 May || A legal [[Montenegrin independence referendum, 2006|Montenegrin independence referendum]]; 55.5% of votes for independence |- | 3 June || Parliament of Montenegro declared the independence of Montenegro, ending the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia . |- | 28 July || Republic of Montenegro recognized as an independent country. |}
===2008=== {| class="wikitable" width="100%" ! width="125" | Date !Event |- | 17 February | [[Republic of Kosovo]] declared [[Independence of Kosovo|independence]] from Serbia and is eventually recognised by {{Numrec|Kos}} UN member states, including 4 of the former Yugoslav states. |}
